In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:

```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

    window.Created       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Created");
    window.Activated     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Activated");
    window.Deactivated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Deactivated");
    window.Stopped       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Stopped");
    window.Resumed       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Resumed");
    window.Destroying    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Destroying");
    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Backgrounding");

    return window;
}
```

**Lifecycle flow (typical):**

| Transition | When |
|---|---|
| `Created` | Window is first created |
| `Activated` | Window receives focus |
| `Deactivated` | Window loses focus |
| `Stopped` | Window is no longer visible |
| `Resumed` | Window returns from stopped state |
| `Backgrounding` | iOS/Mac — app moves to background (use `e.State` to save state) |
| `Destroying` | Window is being torn down |

> **Note:** `Backgrounding` is iOS/macOS only. On Android/Windows the equivalent path is `Stopped`. Use `System.Diagnostics.Debug.WriteLine` so output appears in the IDE's **Debug Output** window.
